<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=7598>


Bluetongue, Israel
------------------
Information received on 10 Dec 2008 from Dr Moshe Chaimovitz,
Director , Veterinary Services and Animal Health, Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Developement, BEIT DAGAN, Israel

Summary:
Report type: Immediate notification
Start date: 05 Nov 2008
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 09 Dec 2008
Report date: 10 Dec 2008
Date submitted to OIE: 10 Dec 2008
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2006
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent: Bluetongue virus
Serotype: Pending
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, Laboratory (basic), Necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks
-------------
Outbreak 1: HAZAV, Ashkelon, HADAROM
Date of start of the outbreak: 05 Nov 2008
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species/ Susceptible/ Cases/ Deaths/ Destroyed/ Slaughtered
Sheep/ 900/ 70/ 15/ 0/ 0
Affected population: Non pregnant ewes were vaccinated after the 1st
clinical signs were observed in the herd.

Outbreak 2: HURA, Beer-Sheva, HADAROM
Date of start of the outbreak: 20 Nov 2008
Outbreak status: Continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: Village
Affected animals
Species/ Susceptible/ Cases/ Deaths/ Destroyed/ Slaughtered
Sheep/ 120/ 30/ 7/ 0/ 0
Affected population: Non pregnant ewes were vaccinated after the 1st
clinical signs were observed in the herd.

Summary of outbreaks
--------------------
Total outbreaks: 2
Total animals affected
Species/ Susceptible/ Cases/ Deaths/ Destroyed/ Slaughtered
Sheep/ 1020/ 100/ 22/ 0/ 0
Outbreak statistics
Species/ Apparent morbidity rate/ Apparent mortality rate/ Apparent
case fatality rate
Sheep/ 9.80 percent/ 2.16 percent/ 22.00 percent

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Vectors
Epidemiological comments: Bluetongue is an endemic disease in Israel
in sheep. 6 serotypes were detected in Israel since 1951 when the
disease was 1st diagnosed: 2, 4, 6, 10, 15 and 16. Serotype 4 is the
most common. The identification of the involved serotype for these
cases is still in progress in the laboratory.

Control measures
Measures applied:
Control of arthropods
Vaccination in response to the outbreak (s) [See comment]
No treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: No other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Kimron Veterinary Institute, Virology
Laboratory (National laboratory)
Tests and results
Species/ Test/ Test date/ Result
Sheep/ pathogen isolation by egg inoculation/ 09 Dec 2008/ Positive
Sheep/ polymerase chain reaction (PCR)/ 09 Dec 2008/ Positive

