Date: Tue 20 Jan 2009
Source: OIE WAHID animal disease interface Weekly Disease Information
Vol. 22 - No. 04, Jan 2009 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=7707>


Bluetongue, Israel
------------------
Information received on 20 Jan 2009 from Dr Moshe Chaimovitz,
Director , Veterinary Services and Animal Health, Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Developement, BEIT DAGAN, Israel

Summary
Report type: Follow-up report No. 1
Start date: 05 Nov 2008
Date of 1st confirmation of the event: 09 Dec 2008
Report date: 20 Jan 2009
Date submitted to OIE: 20 Jan 2009
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 2006
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent: Bluetongue virus
Serotype: Pending
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, Laboratory (basic), Laboratory
(advanced), Necropsy
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks

[A total of 8 outbreaks are covered in this follow-up report (which
we have abridged), of which 3 in sheep holdings, 2 in cattle
holdings, 2 in mixed sheep and cattle holdings (both species
affected), and 1 in a dairy goats operation. All 3 species showed
clinical signs, including mortalities. The place names of the
outbreaks, detailed information on the number of cases, deaths, etc.,
in each of them can be accessed in the original OIE report at the
above URL. The report includes also a map showing the respective 8
locations which are to be seen spread throughout the entire territory
of Israel. - Mod.AS]

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 8
Total animals affected
Species/ Susceptible/ Cases/ Deaths
Cattle/ 251/ 81 [partial data] / 12
Goats 1500 / [not included] / [not included]
Sheep 2000/ 40 [partial data] / 11

Outbreak statistics: Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Vectors

Epidemiological comments: Bluetongue is an endemic disease in Israel
in sheep. 6 serotypes were detected in Israel since 1951 when the
disease was 1st diagnosed: 2, 4, 6, 10, 15 and 16. Serotype 4 is the
most common. The identification of the involved serotype for these
cases is still in progress in the laboratory.

Control measures
Measures applied
- Control of arthropods
- Vaccination in response to the outbreak (s) [see comment]
- Dipping / Spraying
- No treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: No other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Pirbright Laboratory (OIE's Reference Laboratory)
Tests and results
Species/ Test/ Test date/ Result
Cattle/ real-time PCR/ 23 Dec 2008/ Positive
Goats/ real-time PCR/ 23 Dec 2008/ Positive
Sheep/ real-time PCR/ 23 Dec 2008/ Positive

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The total, accumulated number of BTV outbreaks in Israel during
Oct/Nov 2008, reported in the immediate notification of 10 Dec 2008
(item 3 above) and the follow-up report No 1 of 20 Jan 2009 (item 2),
is 10, of which 5 in sheep holdings, 2 in cattle holdings, 2 in mixed
sheep and cattle holdings, and 1 in a dairy goat operation. Clinical
disease and mortality in Israeli cattle and goats is highly unusual.
Although sporadic BT cases in cattle (mostly involving fattening
young bulls) have been seen in the past, they were rare and
exceptional. Clinical BT in goats is extremely rare in Israel. Indeed
a major outbreak of EHD, which cannot be clinically differentiated
from BT, was reported in Israeli cattle in 2006; but according to the
results of the Kimron Veterinary Institute reported in the immediate
notification, and of the OIE reference laboratory in Pirbright,
reported in the follow-up report, samples from cattle have now been
identified as BTV, though serotyping seems to be pending. This may exclude EHD.

The report mentions, among "applied control measures," "vaccination
in response to the outbreak." Since the only BTV vaccine currently
available in Israel is an inactivated bivalent BTV2/BTV4 vaccine
(manufactured in Europe), the efficacy of such vaccine to protect
susceptible animals (which may now include cattle on top of sheep)
against the current causative agent, is questionable. BTV2 and BTV4,
both endemic and long familiar in Israel, would have already been
identified if present in the tested samples.

An early completion of the serotyping, potentially enabling the
purchase (or, if unavailable, the production) of a homologous
inactivated vaccine, is to be wishfully anticipated. Could this be
achieved sufficiently ahead of the 2009 BT season? - Mod.AS]
